abstract: Liberal political parties emerging as surprise runners-up in Tunisia's elections argue that their success has tempered the commanding victory of the Islamists and offers lessons for secular allies around the Mideast.
snippet: Two secular parties that were successful in the Tunisian election cautioned that voters also had been looking to punish candidates who appeared to pick a fight with Islamists.
